the best of the trilogy imo
both Germany and Japan care about efficiency, but their approaches are shaped by different cultural backgrounds
Japan: collectivist, values social harmony and consensus. Technology is adopted if it enhances collective well-being. The restrictive aspects come from a desire to maintain social cohesion
Germany: individualistic, focus on precision engineering and planning. Less emphasis on collective consensus and more on functionality and standards

take the Shinkansen and Autobahn as metaphors:
	
Autobahn: individual freedom within a framework of expertise and shared rules (go as fast as you like on good roads, respect rules)

Shinkansen: collective harmony through rigid protocols (there's a place and protocol for everything, individual deviations not encouraged)
